For `XSSF`the answer ist here: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/58594849/apache-poi-4-1-set-cell-background-color-from-hex-code/58603161#58603161.

That shows a solution for the first problem of how to get a `byte` array from a hex string.

But the binary Excel file system is very different in how to store colors. One cannot simply store a new color as `HSSFColor` as it would be possible for `XSSFColor`. Instead all colors needs to be in a color palette `HSSFPalette` and there are only limited free color slots. So to get a custom `HSSFColor` one either needs to find a similar color in palette or needs overwriting an existent color in palette. I would suggest to find a similar color in palette.

Following code shows how to do that:

    import java.io.FileOutputStream;
    import org.apache.poi.ss.usermodel.*;
    import org.apache.poi.xssf.usermodel.*;
    import org.apache.poi.hssf.usermodel.*;
    import org.apache.poi.hssf.util.HSSFColor;
    
    import org.apache.commons.codec.binary.Hex;
    
    class CreateHSSFColorOrXSSFColor {
    
     public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception {
    
      try (
           //Workbook workbook = new XSSFWorkbook(); FileOutputStream fileout = new FileOutputStream(&quot;./Excel.xlsx&quot;) 
           Workbook workbook = new HSSFWorkbook(); FileOutputStream fileout = new FileOutputStream(&quot;./Excel.xls&quot;) 
    	   
    	   ) {
    
       String rgbS = &quot;C0C0C0&quot;;
       byte[] rgbB = Hex.decodeHex(rgbS); // get byte array from hex string
       
       CellStyle cellStyle = workbook.createCellStyle();
    
       if (workbook instanceof XSSFWorkbook) {
        XSSFColor color = new XSSFColor(rgbB, null);
        ((XSSFCellStyle)cellStyle).setFillForegroundColor(color);
       } else if (workbook instanceof HSSFWorkbook) {
        HSSFPalette	palette = ((HSSFWorkbook)workbook).getCustomPalette();
    	HSSFColor color = null;
    	
    	// either find similar color in palette
    	color = palette.findSimilarColor(rgbB[0], rgbB[1], rgbB[2]);
    	if (color == null) {
         color = palette.addColor(rgbB[0], rgbB[1], rgbB[2]);
        }
    	
    	// or ovwerwrite a indexed color in palette
    	//palette.setColorAtIndex(IndexedColors.LIME.getIndex(), rgbB[0], rgbB[1], rgbB[2]);
    	//color = palette.getColor(IndexedColors.LIME.getIndex());
    	
    	cellStyle.setFillForegroundColor(color.getIndex());
       }
    
       cellStyle.setFillPattern(FillPatternType.SOLID_FOREGROUND);
    
       Sheet sheet = workbook.createSheet(); 
       Row row = sheet.createRow(0);
       Cell cell = row.createCell(0);
       cell.setCellValue(&quot;custom&quot;);
       cell.setCellStyle(cellStyle);
    
       workbook.write(fileout);
      }
    
     }
    }

The code part

	// or ovwerwrite a indexed color in palette
	//palette.setColorAtIndex(IndexedColors.LIME.getIndex(), rgbB[0], rgbB[1], rgbB[2]);
	//color = palette.getColor(IndexedColors.LIME.getIndex());

is commented out. If you uncomment, then the existent palette color LIME gets overwritten with the custom color. Of course the LIME color is then not more reachable.

