In JavaFX, to achieve the layout you&#39;re describing—where the two buttons are always on the far right and the label takes up all the remaining space—you can use a combination of `HBox`, `Region`, and `HBox.setHgrow`.

Here&#39;s how:

 1. Create a `Region` that will act as a spacer between your label and buttons.
 2. Use `HBox.setHgrow` to make the `Region` take up all the available space.

Here&#39;s a code example:


    import javafx.application.Application;
    import javafx.scene.Scene;
    import javafx.scene.control.Button;
    import javafx.scene.control.Label;
    import javafx.scene.layout.HBox;
    import javafx.scene.layout.Priority;
    import javafx.scene.layout.Region;
    import javafx.stage.Stage;
    
    public class Main extends Application {
    
        @Override
        public void start(Stage primaryStage) {
            Label label = new Label(&quot;Or lots and lots and lots of text.&quot;);
            
            Button buttonX = new Button(&quot;buttonX&quot;);
            Button buttonY = new Button(&quot;buttonY&quot;);
            
            // Create a region to act as a horizontal spacer
            Region spacer = new Region();
            
            // Make the spacer Region expand as much as possible
            HBox.setHgrow(spacer, Priority.ALWAYS);
            
            HBox hbox = new HBox(label, spacer, buttonX, buttonY);
            
            Scene scene = new Scene(hbox, 400, 100);
            
            primaryStage.setScene(scene);
            primaryStage.show();
        }
    
        public static void main(String[] args) {
            launch(args);
        }
    }

In this example, the `Region` named `spacer` will take up all the extra horizontal space in the `HBox`, pushing your buttons to the far right. The label will take up only as much space as it needs for its text, while `spacer` fills up the remaining space. This ensures your buttons remain on the far right regardless of the label&#39;s width.

To place a button on a specific point of a zoomed image and ensure that it stays at that point relative to the image (not the mobile display), you need to consider both the zoom factor and the position of the button. You can achieve this by using a custom ImageView and handling the touch event coordinates.

Here&#39;s a basic outline of how you can achieve this in Java in an Android application:

Create a custom ImageView that allows zooming. You can use libraries like PhotoView for this purpose.

Inside your custom ImageView, override the onTouchEvent method to capture the touch coordinates.

Adjust the coordinates based on the zoom factor to place the button correctly.

Create a button and add it to the layout, specifying the calculated coordinates.

Here&#39;s an example code snippet to illustrate the idea:
```
public class CustomZoomableImageView extends PhotoView {
    private Button button;

    public CustomZoomableImageView(Context context) {
        super(context);
        initializeButton(context);
    }

    private void initializeButton(Context context) {
        button = new Button(context);
        button.setText(&quot;My Button&quot;);
        button.setOnClickListener(new View.OnClickListener() {
            @Override
            public void onClick(View v) {
                // Handle button click here
            }
        });
        addView(button);
    }

    @Override
    public boolean onTouchEvent(MotionEvent event) {
        float x = event.getX();
        float y = event.getY();

        // Adjust x and y based on the zoom factor
        Matrix matrix = getDisplayMatrix();
        float[] values = new float[9];
        matrix.getValues(values);
        float scaleFactor = values[Matrix.MSCALE_X];

        float adjustedX = x / scaleFactor;
        float adjustedY = y / scaleFactor;

        // Set the button&#39;s position
        button.setX(adjustedX);
        button.setY(adjustedY);

        return super.onTouchEvent(event);
    }
}

```

In this example, CustomZoomableImageView is a custom ImageView that extends PhotoView (you can replace this with your zoomable view). It overrides onTouchEvent to capture touch coordinates and adjusts them based on the zoom factor. The button is created and positioned based on the adjusted coordinates.

Please note that this is a simplified example, and you may need to adapt it to your specific use case and layout. You also need to consider how to handle button placement and persistence when the image is re-zoomed.

