&gt; cannot find symbol variable operator

This error was caused by `char choice = operator.charAt(0);` in your `getString(string)` method. The `operator` is not declared in that context and it only available to the `main` method.

&gt; cannot find symbol variable calculator2Object

The `calculator2Object` inside `getString(string)` is not declared and instantiated anywhere in the method previously. You should instantiate the variable before using it (e.g. `Calculator2 calculator2Object = new Calculator2();`). Alternatively, just set `double add(double, double)` as `static`.

&gt; cannot find symbol variable result

Triggered by `return result = operator;`, the `result` variable is not declared at all in the `getString(string)` method. Remember, stuff inside `Calculator2` methods can&#39;t be accessed by `getString(string)` unless its a property or `return`-ed.

---

The reason I suggested for trying to build up the code from the main method then divide them up as you find repetitive code is so that you have a working sample and to learn about variable scopes.

Looking at the given boiler plate, I suspect it was to accomodate most of the repetitive part of the code: asking user input.

    private static final Scanner inputScanner = new Scanner(System.in);

    private static String getString(String prompt) {  }

    private static double getDouble(String prompt) {  }

Think this way, if you did not use the `getString(string)` or `getDouble(string)`, you may end up having multiple of:

    System.out.println(&quot;What is the first number:&quot;);
    double operand = Double.parseDouble(inputScanner.nextLine());

If you complete the `getDouble(string)` into:

    private static String getDouble(String prompt)
    {
        System.out.println(prompt);
        return Double.parseDouble(inputScanner.nextLine());
    }

You can prompt while assigning the result into variable by doing the following instead:

    double operand = getDouble(&quot;What is the first number:&quot;);

You can complete the `getString(string)` in similar fashion - its optional anyway.

The next part would be calling the appropriate method in `Calculator2`. You could simply turn the method into `static`. So that you can call them using `Calculator2.add(operand1, operand2)` directly from the `main` method.

    static double add(double firstNumber, double secondNumber) {
        double result = firstNumber + secondNumber;
        System.out.println(result);
        return result;
    }

Once you have completed those fixes, your main method will be (kinda) shorter - arguably you can get even shorter and more efficient though.

    public static void main(String args[]) {
        String operator = getString(&quot;What would you like to do?&quot;);
        char choice = operator.charAt(0);
        switch (choice) {
            case &#39;a&#39;:
                double operand1 = getDouble(&quot;Enter the first number:&quot;);
                double operand2 = getDouble(&quot;Enter the second number:&quot;);
                Calculator2.add(operand1, operand2);
                break;
                    //the other operators
            case &#39;e&#39;:
                System.out.println(&quot;Goodbye&quot;);
                System.exit(0);
        }
    }

