```

The code needs to be modified so that only `|&lt;3|` **or** `|##|` is printed, not both at the same time.

Looking at the expected output, we can see that the &quot;steps&quot; alternate both in the horizontal direction and the vertical direction. In the code, we have access to `x` and `y`. These two numbers are also alternating between even and odd. And if we look at the values of `x` and `y` for each step we&#39;ll see a pattern. A `|&lt;3|` will only be printed when `x` is _odd_ and `y` is _even_, or vice versa&lt;sup&gt;1&lt;/sup&gt;. In other words, a `|&lt;3|` will only be printed when `x` and `y` have _different [parity][2]_.

Using that knowledge, we can modify the original code to give us&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt;:

```java
public class Main {

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int numberOfSteps = 8;
        for (int y = 1; y &lt;= numberOfSteps; y++) {
            for (int x = 1; x &lt;= numberOfSteps; x++) {
                if (x &gt; numberOfSteps - y) {
                    if (x % 2 != y % 2) {
                        System.out.print(&quot;|&lt;3|&quot;);
                    } else {
                        System.out.print(&quot;|##|&quot;);
                    }
                } else {
                    System.out.print(&quot;|  |&quot;);
                }
            }
            System.out.println();
        }
    }
}
```

