Since the variable `data` is of type `Optional&lt;T&gt;`, the same has to be passed while initializing the object as well

```
APIResponse&lt;String&gt; responseWithData = new APIResponse&lt;&gt;(&quot;Success&quot;, HttpStatus.OK, Optional.of(&quot;HEY&quot;));

APIResponse&lt;CustomDTO&gt; apiResponse = new APIResponse&lt;&gt;(&quot;Success&quot;, HttpStatus.OK, Optional.of(this.customDTO));
```

Having said that, there are also a couple of variations you could do if it applies to your use case

Declaring variable `data` of type `T` and not as Optional, i.e.

```
public class APIResponse&lt;T&gt; {
    private String message;
    private HttpStatus httpStatus;
    private T data;
}

APIResponse&lt;String&gt; responseWithData = new APIResponse&lt;&gt;(&quot;Success&quot;, HttpStatus.OK, &quot;HEY&quot;);

APIResponse&lt;CustomDTO&gt; apiResponse = new APIResponse&lt;&gt;(&quot;Success&quot;, HttpStatus.OK, this.customDTO);

```

Or you could avoid using the generic type `T` and use the wildcard `?` which represents the unknown type (as discussed in the comments)

```
public class APIResponse {
    private String message;
    private HttpStatus httpStatus;
    private Optional&lt;?&gt; data;
}

APIResponse responseWithData = new APIResponse(&quot;Success&quot;, HttpStatus.OK, Optional.of(&quot;HEY&quot;));

APIResponse apiResponse = new APIResponse(&quot;Success&quot;, HttpStatus.OK, Optional.of(this.customDTO));

```

