**Hint:**

A method that accepts 3 (integer) parameters would look like this ...

    public static int findMin(int p1, int p2, int p3) {
        ...
    }

The problem is that you allow the user to only specify 1 parameter while the requirement is 3, after which you hardcode two others yourself.

A simple solution could be this:

	private static int findMin(int arg0, int arg1, int arg2) {
		int low = arg0;
		low = Math.min(low, arg1);
		low = Math.min(low, arg2);
		
		return low;
	}

* Assign the first parameter to the variable &#39;low&#39;
* Keep comparing this variable to the other parameters and assign the result of it to `low`

You could also put the ints into an array and sort it. The first element will be the smallest, therfore the minimum.

    public static int findMin(int int1, int int2, int int3) {
        int[] nums={int1, int2, int3};
        Arrays.sort(nums);
        return nums[0];
    }

Or just use composition:

    public static int findMin(int a, int b, int c) {
	    return Math.min(Math.min(a, b), c);
	}

